{{other uses|Family values (disambiguation)}}
{{Conservatism US}}
'''Family values''', sometimes referred to as '''familial values''', are [[tradition]]al or cultural [[values]] that pertain to the [[family]]'s structure, function, roles, beliefs, attitudes, and ideals.

In the social sciences and U.S. political discourse, the term "[[traditional family]]" refers to a nuclear family − a child-rearing environment composed of a [[breadwinner|breadwinning]] [[father]], a [[homemaking]] [[mother]], and their biological [[children]]; sociologists formerly referred to this model as the [[Social norm|norm]].{{fact|date=May 2018}} A family deviating from this model is considered a [[Non-traditional family|nontraditional family]].  However, in most cultures at most times, the [[extended family]] model has been most common, not the nuclear family,<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2018/05/13/610777733/parenting-myths-and-facts Parenting Myths And Facts]</ref> and the nuclear family became the most common form in the U.S. in the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>[https://bebusinessed.com/history/history-nuclear-families/ History of Nuclear Families]</ref>

==Definition==
Several well-known online dictionaries define "family values" as the following:
* "the [[morality|moral]] and [[ethics|ethical]] principles traditionally upheld and passed on within a family, as honesty, loyalty, industry, and faith."<ref>{{cite web|title=family values|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/family+values|website=Dictionary.com|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref>
* "values especially of a traditional or [[Conservatism|conservative]] kind which are held to promote the sound functioning of the family and to strengthen the fabric of society."<ref>{{cite web|title=family values|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/family%20values|website=Merriam-Webster|publisher=Merriam-Webster, Inc.|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref>
* "values held to be traditionally taught or reinforced within a family, such as those of high moral standards and discipline."<ref>{{cite web|title=family values|url=http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/us/definition/american_english/family-values|website=Oxford Dictionaries|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref>

==In politics==
{{Main|Familialism}}
[[Familialism]] or ''familism'' is the [[ideology]] that puts priority on [[family]] and family values.<ref name=Ochiai>{{cite book|title=Transformation of the Intimate and the Public in Asian Modernity. The Intimate and the Public in Asian and Global Perspectives|author=Emiko Ochiai, Leo Aoi Hosoya|publisher=BRILL|year=2014|isbn=9789004264359}} [url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JImIBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA20 Page 20-21]</ref> Familialism prioritizes the needs of the family over the needs of individuals, and advocates for a welfare system where families, rather than the [[government]], take responsibility for the care of their members.<ref name=Ochiai/>

In the United States, the banner of "family values" has been used by [[Conservatism in the United States|conservatives]] to fight [[abortion]], [[LGBT rights|gay rights]], and major [[Feminism|feminist]] objectives in politics.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dowland|first1=Seth|title=Family Values and the Rise of the Christian Right|date=2015|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=9780812247602|url=to fight abortion, gay rights, and major feminist objectives}}</ref>

==In culture==
{{missing information|other cultures|date=November 2016}}

===Saudi culture===
Interpretations of [[Islam]]ic learnings and [[Arab culture]] are common for the majority of [[Saudi]]s. [[Islam]] is a driving cultural force that dictates a submission to the will of [[God]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Peachy|first1=William S.|title=A brief look upon Islam|date=1999|publisher=Darussalam Publishers and Distributors|location=Riyadh, Saudi Arabia|pages=48|url=https://www.amazon.com/A-Brief-Look-Upon-Islam/dp/B00135EA0W|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref> The academic literature suggests that the family is regarded as the main foundation of Muslim society and culture; the family structure and nature of the relationship between family members are influenced by the Islamic religion.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Mutair, A|author2=Plummer, V|author3=O'Brien, A|author4= Clerehan, R|authorlink1=Providing culturally congruent care for Saudi patients and their families|journal=Contemporary Nurse: A Journal For The Australian Nursing Profession|date=2014|volume=46|issue=2|pages=254–258}}</ref> Marriage in Saudi culture means the union of two families, not just two individuals.<ref>{{cite journal|author1= Khalaf, I|author2=Callister, L|title=Cultural meanings of childbirth: Muslim women living in Jordan|journal=Journal of Holistic Nursing|date=1997|volume=4|issue=15|pages=373–388}}</ref> In Muslim society, marriage involves a social contract that occurs with the consent of [[parent]]s or guardians. Furthermore, marriage is considered the only legitimate outlet for [[sexual desire]]s, and sex outside marriage ([[fornication]]) is a crime that is punished under Islamic law.<ref>{{cite book|author1= Lemu, A|author2=Heeren, F|title=Women in Islam|date=1992|publisher=The Islamic Foundation|location=Leicester, England|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref> This view of marriage is similar to the [[Western world|Western]] [[Christian]] view of marriage, created in 12th century [[France]], which promised [[salvation]], sex without sin, and much more.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McDougall|first1= Sara|title= The Making of Marriage in Medieval France|journal=Journal of Family History|date= 2013|volume= 38|issue=2|pages= 103–121}}</ref>

The Saudi family includes extended families, as the [[extended family]] provides the individual with a sense of [[Identity (social science)|identity]]. The father is often the [[:wikt:breadwinner|breadwinner]] and protector of the family, whereas the mother is often the [[homemaker]] and the primary caretaker of the children.<ref>{{cite journal|last1= Luna|first1=J|title= Transcultural nursing care of Arab Muslims|journal=Journal of Transcultural Nursing|date=1989|volume=1|issue=1|pages=22–26}}</ref> Parents are regarded with high respect, and children are strongly encouraged to respect and obey their parents.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Ghazwi, F.|author2= Nock, L.|authorlink1= Religion as mediating force in the effects of modernization on parent–child relations in Jordan|journal=Middle Eastern Studies|date=1989|volume=25|pages= 363–369}}</ref> Often, families provide care for elders. Until recently, because families and friends are expected to provide [[elderly care]], [[nursing home]]s were considered culturally unacceptable.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Luna|first1= J|title=Transcultural nursing care of Arab Muslims|journal=Journal of Transcultural Nursing|date=1989|volume=1 |issue= 1|pages= 22–26}}</ref>

===United States culture===
In sociological terms, nontraditional families make up the majority of American households.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Panasenko, N|title=Czech and Slovak Family Patterns and Family Values in Historical, Social and Cultural Context|journal=Journal of Comparative Family Studies|date=2013|volume=44|issue=1|pages=79–98}}</ref> As of 2014, only 46% of children in the U.S. live in a traditional family, down from 61% in 1980.<ref>http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2014/12/22/less-than-half-of-u-s-kids-today-live-in-a-traditional-family/</ref> This number includes only families with parents who are in their first marriage, whereas the percentage of children simply living with two married parents is 65% as of 2016.<ref>https://www.census.gov/newsroom/press-releases/2016/cb16-192.html</ref> However, there are many who hold that the nuclear family is the fabric that holds society together<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bruderhof.com/en/our-faith/foundations/church-actions/marriage|title=Marriage|website=Bruderhof|language=en|access-date=2018-01-17}}</ref> and work to promote stronger family values. The [[Chemin Neuf Community|Chemin Neuf]] community, the [[Bruderhof Communities|Bruderhof]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/dreher/life-among-the-bruderhof/|title=Life Among The Bruderhof|work=The American Conservative|access-date=2018-01-17|language=en-us}}</ref> and the [[Evangelical Alliance]] all work to promote the nuclear family.

